column4: <content>Ad [Addendum] Sermon of St. John. The theme is conversion: There are pagans (Islam: man in turban), jews (Rabby), gipsies [sic], people possessed by demons (epileptic) who all need conversion to true faith- which is Christ. St John is pointing to Christ as the true salvation. On the right, on the sight of Christ, are the adherents of Christ, on the hill, and [onleesbaar] Franciscan monks (seen positively)(and on the right is the Baptism of Christ). If in the group on the hill is a self-portrait, this does not mean Anabaptists, only that these converted to true faith include Bruegel himself. As for epileptic see: Werner DANCKERT, Unehrliche Leute: die verfemten Berufe, Bern, München [Francke], 1963, [citaat] p. 231. As subject of conversion: the Sermon of St. John has its counterpart in the Conversion of St. Paul.[woord onderaan in potlood: onleesbaar]</content>
<object.title>The Sermon of St. John the Baptist</object.title>
